Project Overview

This project develops a machine learning model to predict hotel prices using a structured approach. It begins with data preparation, including exploratory data analysis, visualization, and feature engineering to uncover patterns and optimize data for modeling. Next, models like Naive Bayes, Decision Trees, Random Forests, and XGBoost are trained and fine-tuned through techniques such as normalization and hyperparameter optimization. Finally, the models are evaluated using metrics like accuracy, precision, and F1-score, with results documented in a Jupyter Notebook for clarity and reproducibility.

Calculating Price per Night per Adult¶

To standardize the price in the dataset, we calculate the price per night per adult using the following steps:

  1. Extract Price: Ensure the price column contains only the numeric part.

  2. Extract Nights: Ensure the nights column contains only numeric values.

  3. Extract Adults: Ensure the adults column contains only numeric values.

  4. Calculate Standardized Price: Use the formula:

    $\text{Price per night per adult} = \frac{\text{price}}{\text{nights} \times \text{adults}}$

  5. Replace the Original Price Column: Update the price column with this calculated value to standardize it across all records.

  6. Drop Unnecessary Columns: Remove the nights and adults columns if they are no longer needed for the analysis.

In [10]:
hotels_df['price'] = hotels_df['price'].replace(',', '', regex=True).astype(float)
hotels_df['nights'] = hotels_df['nights'].astype(int)
hotels_df['adults'] = hotels_df['adults'].astype(int)

hotels_df['price'] = hotels_df['price'] / (hotels_df['nights'] * hotels_df['adults'])

hotels_df.drop(columns=['nights', 'adults'], inplace=True)

hotels_df['price'] = hotels_df['price'].replace([np.inf, -np.inf], np.nan)

🛠 Handling Missing Values 💡¶

There are several ways to handle missing numerical values in a dataset, some of which include:

  • Deleting rows with missing values : This approach simply removes any rows that contain missing values, but it can be problematic if a large portion of the dataset contains missing values.

  • Imputing with mean or median : This method involves replacing the missing values with the mean or median of the existing values in that column. This approach can work well if the distribution of the data is normal, but it may not be suitable for skewed data.

  • Imputing with regression : This method involves using a regression model to predict the missing values based on other variables in the dataset. This approach can work well if there is a strong correlation between the missing value and other variables in the dataset.

  • Using a clustering algorithm : This method involves using clustering algorithms to group similar data points together and then imputing the missing values with the mean or median value of the cluster. This approach can work well if there is a clear clustering structure in the data.

  • Using the K-Nearest Neighbors algorithm: This method involves finding the K nearest neighbors of the missing value and imputing the missing value with the average of the K nearest neighbors. This approach can work well if there is a strong correlation between the missing value and its nearest neighbors.

The choice of method depends on the nature of the missing data and the analysis goals.

Filling Missing Values for the rating Feature¶

Recommended Approach:

  • Use the median rating specific to each restaurant for imputation. If a restaurant has no available ratings, fall back to the overall median.

Rationale:

  • The restaurant-specific median offers a more precise estimate, reflecting the typical rating for that restaurant.

  • The overall median acts as a reliable fallback, ensuring no data is left untreated.

  • This strategy effectively handles missing values while maintaining robustness against outliers, preserving the integrity of the data.

In [17]:
median_rating_per_restaurant = hotels_df.groupby('name')['rating'].transform('median')

hotels_df['rating'] = hotels_df['rating'].fillna(median_rating_per_restaurant)

# if any NaN values remain we replace it with the overall median
overall_median_rating = hotels_df['rating'].median()
hotels_df['rating'] = hotels_df['rating'].fillna(overall_median_rating)

Filling Missing Values for the quality Feature¶

Recommended Approach:

  • Replace missing values in the quality feature with the maximum quality value for each restaurant.

Rationale:

  • Using the maximum quality value for each restaurant ensures a consistent and optimistic representation of missing data.

  • This approach leverages existing information while avoiding arbitrary assumptions, maintaining data integrity.

  • It effectively fills gaps in the dataset, supporting robust model performance.

hotels_df['quality'] = hotels_df.groupby('name')['quality'].transform(

Filling Missing Values for the review Feature¶

Recommended Approach:

  • Replace missing values in the review feature with the median number of reviews for the same hotel (name).

Rationale:

  • Using the median reflects the central tendency of reviews for each hotel, assuming consistency among its review counts.

  • This approach maintains data integrity while reducing the impact of outliers.

  • It ensures the dataset remains complete and reliable for further analysis.

In [19]:
global_median = hotels_df['review'].median()

def fill_with_group_median(group):
    if group.isna().all():  # if the entire group is NaN
        return group.fillna(global_median)
    return group.fillna(group.median())

hotels_df['review'] = hotels_df.groupby('name')['review'].transform(fill_with_group_median)

Filling Missing Values for the bed Feature¶

Recommended Approach:

  • Fill missing values in the bed feature using the mode (most frequent value) within each group of hotels, grouped by their name.

Rationale:

  • The mode represents the most common value for each group, making it a reliable fill for missing data within each hotel.

  • If a group has no mode (e.g., all values are NaN or unique), no replacement will occur, avoiding inappropriate imputation.

  • This approach ensures that missing values are handled in a way that reflects the typical value for each hotel, maintaining consistency in the dataset.

In [20]:
def fill_with_group_mode(group):
    if group.mode().empty:
        return #if mode cannot be calculated
    return group.fillna(group.mode()[0])

hotels_df['bed'] = hotels_df.groupby('name')['bed'].transform(fill_with_group_mode)

Filling Missing Values for the city Feature¶

Recommended Approach:

  • Fill missing values in the city feature by using the city of the same restaurant (if available) or the city of a neighboring restaurant.

Rationale:

  • The approach first attempts to fill the missing city value using the city of the same restaurant (by matching the name column) if it exists in the dataset.

  • If no matching restaurant is found, the method checks the city of neighboring restaurants (previous or next rows) to fill the missing value, ensuring the value is reasonably assigned.

  • This approach makes use of existing data from the same restaurant or its neighbors to ensure consistency in the dataset while maintaining the accuracy of location information for each restaurant.

In [21]:
def fill_city_with_name_or_neighbor(df):
    for i in range(len(df)):
        if pd.isna(df.loc[i, 'city']):
            if df['name'].iloc[:i].eq(df.loc[i, 'name']).any():
                df.loc[i, 'city'] = df.loc[i - 1, 'city']
            elif df['name'].iloc[i + 1:].eq(df.loc[i, 'name']).any():
                df.loc[i, 'city'] = df.loc[i + 1, 'city']
            #check neighbors
            elif i > 0 and pd.notna(df.loc[i - 1, 'city']):
                df.loc[i, 'city'] = df.loc[i - 1, 'city']  # Use previous row city
            elif i < len(df) - 1 and pd.notna(df.loc[i + 1, 'city']):
                df.loc[i, 'city'] = df.loc[i + 1, 'city']  # Use next row city
    
    return df

hotels_df = fill_city_with_name_or_neighbor(hotels_df)

🌐 Normalizing Numerical Features in the Dataset¶

Approach:

  • We normalize the rating, review, and distance_from_center features to ensure they are on the same scale, which is important for many machine learning algorithms ⚙️.

Methods Used:

  1. Min-Max Scaling:

    • Scales features to a range between [0, 1]. This is useful when you need to preserve the relationships between the original data points within a fixed range.

    • Applied using MinMaxScaler() from sklearn.

  2. Standardization (commented out):

    • Scales features to have a mean of 0 and a standard deviation of 1. This is useful when working with algorithms that assume normally distributed data or when managing outliers.

    • Applied using StandardScaler() from sklearn.

Reason for Normalization:

  • Normalizing the features ensures that no single feature dominates others due to differences in scale. Many machine learning algorithms, such as KNN or SVM, rely on distance metrics, and features with larger ranges could disproportionately influence the model. Normalization helps to achieve fair treatment of each feature, improving model performance.

🚀 Deploying Sklearn Models¶

In this section, we use built-in models from the sklearn library for the classification task. And show the complete classification report, including the confusion matrix, precision, recall, F1-score, and accuracy 📊.

🧪 Analyzing Model Performance¶

  1. Confusion Matrix :

    Displays the true positive, false positive, true negative, and false negative counts for each class.

  2. Accuracy :

    The ratio of correctly predicted samples to the total samples.

  3. Precision, Recall, and F1-Score :

    • Calculated for each class and averages.

    • Precision: $\frac{\text{True Positives}}{\text{True Positives } + \text{ False Positives}}$

    • Recall: $\frac{\text{True Positives}}{\text{True Positives} + \text{ False Negatives}}$

    • F1-Score: Harmonic mean of precision and recall.

  4. Averaging Methods :

    • Micro : Aggregates contributions from all classes, treating every instance equally.

    • Macro : Calculates metrics independently for each class and then takes the mean, treating all classes equally.

    • Weighted : Accounts for the imbalance in class distribution by weighting metrics by class frequency.

In [37]:
def evaluate_model(model_name, model, y_test):
    
    y_pred = model.predict(X_test)
    
    plt.figure(figsize=(5, 5))
    sns.heatmap(confusion_matrix(y_test, y_pred), annot=True, fmt='d', cmap='Blues', cbar=False)
    plt.title(f'{model_name} Confusion Matrix')
    plt.ylabel('Actual')
    plt.xlabel('Predicted')
    plt.show()
    
    accuracy = accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred)
    print(f"\nAccuracy: {accuracy:.4f}")

    precision = precision_score(y_test, y_pred, average=None)
    recall = recall_score(y_test, y_pred, average=None)
    f1 = f1_score(y_test, y_pred, average=None)

    print("\nPrecision per class:", precision)
    print("\nRecall per class:", recall)
    print("\nF1-Score per class:", f1)

    weighted_precision = precision_score(y_test, y_pred, average='weighted')
    weighted_recall = recall_score(y_test, y_pred, average='weighted')
    weighted_f1 = f1_score(y_test, y_pred, average='weighted')

    micro_precision = precision_score(y_test, y_pred, average='micro')
    micro_recall = recall_score(y_test, y_pred, average='micro')
    micro_f1 = f1_score(y_test, y_pred, average='micro')

    macro_precision = precision_score(y_test, y_pred, average='macro')
    macro_recall = recall_score(y_test, y_pred, average='macro')
    macro_f1 = f1_score(y_test, y_pred, average='macro')

    print("\nWeighted Averages:")
    print(f"Precision: {weighted_precision:.4f}, Recall: {weighted_recall:.4f}, F1-Score: {weighted_f1:.4f}")

    print("\nMicro Averages:")
    print(f"Precision: {micro_precision:.4f}, Recall: {micro_recall:.4f}, F1-Score: {micro_f1:.4f}")

    print("\nMacro Averages:")
    print(f"Precision: {macro_precision:.4f}, Recall: {macro_recall:.4f}, F1-Score: {macro_f1:.4f}")

🌳 Decision Tree Classifier¶

⚒️ Decision Tree Classifier Implementation¶

  1. Pruning with Hyperparameters:

    • max_depth: Limits tree depth to prevent overfitting.

    • min_samples_split: Minimum samples required to split a node.

    • min_samples_leaf: Minimum samples in a leaf node.

    • ccp_alpha: Controls cost-complexity pruning, balancing tree complexity and accuracy.

  2. Hyperparameter Optimization:

    • GridSearchCV: Exhaustively searches for the best hyperparameter combination.

    • cv=5: 5-fold cross-validation for more reliable evaluation.

  3. Code Implementation:

    • Hyperparameters are defined in param_grid.

    • GridSearchCV is used to find optimal parameters, with the best ones retrieved via grid_search.best_params_.

In [40]:
param_grid = {
    'criterion': ['gini', 'entropy'],
    'max_depth': [None, 5, 10, 20],
    'min_samples_split': [2, 5, 10],
    'min_samples_leaf': [1, 2, 5],
    'ccp_alpha': [0.0, 0.01, 0.1]
}

dt_model = DecisionTreeClassifier(random_state=42)

grid_search = GridSearchCV(estimator=dt_model, param_grid=param_grid, cv=5, scoring='accuracy', n_jobs=-1)

grid_search.fit(X_train, y_train)

best_model = grid_search.best_estimator_
print("Best Hyperparameters:", grid_search.best_params_)

🌲🌳 Random Forest Classifier¶

⚒️ Random Forest Classifier Implementation¶

  1. Model Setup:

    • RandomForestClassifier: Combines decision trees for better accuracy and robustness.

    • random_state=42: Ensures reproducibility.

  2. Hyperparameter Tuning with RandomizedSearchCV:

    • RandomizedSearchCV: Efficiently samples a subset of hyperparameter combinations.

    • param_dist: Defines hyperparameters like n_estimators, max_depth, min_samples_split, etc.

    • n_iter=100, cv=5, n_jobs=-1, random_state=42: Samples 100 combinations with 5-fold cross-validation and parallel computation.

  3. Best Hyperparameters:

    • random_search.best_params_: Retrieves the best hyperparameter combination.

  4. Model Evaluation:

    • random_search.best_estimator_: Extracts the best model for predictions and evaluates accuracy on the test set.

  5. Benefits of RandomizedSearchCV:

    • More efficient than GridSearchCV, especially for large hyperparameter spaces.

    • Balances cost and search comprehensiveness, quickly identifying a strong baseline model.

In [43]:
rf_model = RandomForestClassifier(random_state=42)

param_dist = {
    'n_estimators': [100, 200, 300, 500, 1000],

⚡️ Adaptive Boosting¶

⚒️ Adaptive Boosting implementation¶

  1. Model Overview :

    • AdaBoostClassifier : Adaptive Boosting combines multiple "weak learners" (default: DecisionTreeClassifier with max_depth=1) to create a strong ensemble model.

    • random_state=42 : Ensures reproducibility of results.

  2. Hyperparameter Tuning with RandomizedSearchCV :

    • RandomizedSearchCV : Efficiently searches over the hyperparameter space to find the best combination of hyperparameters.

    • param_dist : Specifies the hyperparameters to tune:

      • n_estimators : Number of weak learners (trees) to fit.

      • learning_rate : Shrinks the contribution of each tree to prevent overfitting.

      • algorithm : Boosting algorithm to use (SAMME or SAMME.R).

    • n_iter=100 : Evaluates 100 random combinations of hyperparameters.

    • cv=5 : Performs 5-fold cross-validation to evaluate the performance of each hyperparameter setting.

    • n_jobs=-1 : Utilizes all available processors for faster computation.

    • random_search.best_params_ : Extracts the best hyperparameters from the search.

  3. Code Implementation :

    • The first part applies RandomizedSearchCV to tune hyperparameters, focusing on key parameters like n_estimators, learning_rate, and algorithm.

    • The second part evaluates and plots the effect of n_estimators by training multiple AdaBoost models with different values and comparing their accuracy.

  4. Benefits of AdaBoost :

    • Combines weak learners iteratively to reduce bias and variance.

    • Handles both binary and multi-class classification problems effectively.

    • Offers flexibility in adjusting learning_rate and n_estimators to achieve optimal performance.

  5. Conclusion :

    • AdaBoost’s performance depends significantly on the choice of hyperparameters.

    • Visualizing accuracy trends helps determine the ideal number of estimators for a specific dataset.

In [45]:
ada_model = AdaBoostClassifier(random_state=42)

📊 Analyzing Adaptive Boosting Model with difference n_estimators¶

  1. Effect of n_estimators :

    • A loop is used to evaluate the effect of varying n_estimators on model performance.

    • Models are trained with different values of n_estimators, and their accuracy scores on the test set are recorded.

    • The plot shows how the accuracy changes with the number of estimators (n_estimators).

n_estimators_values = [50, 100, 200]
accuracies = []
for n_estimators in n_estimators_values:

    ada_model = AdaBoostClassifier(n_estimators=n_estimators, random_state=42)

    ada_model.fit(X_train, y_train)

    y_pred = ada_model.predict(X_test)

    accuracy = accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred)
    accuracies.append(accuracy)
    print(f"n_estimators = {n_estimators}: Accuracy = {accuracy:.4f}")

plt.figure(figsize=(8, 5))
plt.plot(n_estimators_values, accuracies, marker='o', linestyle='-', color='b')
plt.title("Effect of n_estimators on AdaBoost Accuracy")
plt.xlabel("Number of Estimators (n_estimators)")
plt.ylabel("Accuracy")
plt.grid(True)
plt.xticks(n_estimators_values)
plt.show()

⚡️ XGBoost¶

⚒️ XGBoost Implementation¶

  1. Model Overview:

    • XGBClassifier: A gradient boosting model for high-performance classification.

    • use_label_encoder=False: Disables default label encoding.

    • eval_metric='logloss': Uses log loss for binary classification.

    • random_state=42: Ensures reproducibility.

  2. Hyperparameter Tuning with GridSearchCV:

    • GridSearchCV: Exhaustively searches hyperparameters.

    • param_grid: Defines hyperparameters like learning_rate, n_estimators, max_depth, etc.

    • cv=5: Uses 5-fold cross-validation.

    • n_jobs=-1: Utilizes all CPU cores for faster computation.

    • grid_search.best_params_: Retrieves the best hyperparameters.

  3. Model Training and Evaluation:

    • grid_search.fit(X_train, y_train): Trains the model with hyperparameter tuning.

    • grid_search.best_score_: Best cross-validation score.

    • accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred): Evaluates accuracy on the test set.

  4. Results and Insights:

    • Outputs the Best Parameters, Cross-Validation Accuracy, and Test Accuracy to evaluate model performance.

  5. Code Implementation:

    • Initializes the model and performs grid search, then evaluates with the test set.

  6. Benefits of XGBoost:

    • Efficiency: Built-in regularization to avoid overfitting.

    • Performance: Delivers state-of-the-art results.

    • Flexibility: Fine-tuning capabilities for improved accuracy.

🛠 From Scratch¶

In this section, we implement the SAMME algorithm for adaptive boosting from scratch.Then we deploy this boosting model and a base estimator, which is Gaussian Naive Bayes here, to classify hotels.

⚒️ SAMME algorithm implementation¶

In [50]:
class SimpleMultiClassBoosting(BaseEstimator, ClassifierMixin):
    def __init__(self, base_estimator=GaussianNB, n_estimators=50):
        self.base_estimator = base_estimator if base_estimator is not None else GaussianNB()
        self.n_estimators = n_estimators
        self.learners = []
        self.learner_weights = []

    def fit(self, X, y):
        n_samples, n_classes = X.shape[0], len(np.unique(y))
        self.weights = (1/n_samples) * np.ones(n_samples, dtype=float) # initialize weights uniformly
        for _ in range(self.n_estimators):
            learner = GaussianNB() # instanciate model
            learner.fit(X, y, sample_weight=self.weights) # fit to samples, using weights
            pred = learner.predict(X) # predict the batch
            missClassified = pred != y # get index of misclassified samples
            
            # TODO : compute learner error rate according to SAMME algorithm
            error_rate = np.sum(self.weights[missClassified])
            
            # TODO : compute learner weight using SAMME algorithm
            learner_weight = np.log((1 - error_rate) / error_rate) + np.log(n_classes - 1)
            
            # TODO : a classifier with error rate which is worse than random should be dropped
            # hint : error rate of untrained classifier : 1 - (1 / n_classes)
            if error_rate >= 1 - (1 / n_classes):
                break

            # TODO : increase the weights of misclassified samples according to SAMME algorithm
            self.weights[missClassified] *= np.exp(learner_weight)
            self.weights /= np.sum(self.weights)
            self.learners.append(learner)
            
            # TODO : store learner weight in self.learner_weights
            self.learner_weights.append(learner_weight)

    def predict(self, X):
        # note that X can contain multiple samples in shape of array, in which, each row corresponds to a query
        predictionsOfLearners = []
        for learner in self.learners:
            predictionsOfLearners.append(learner.predict(X)) # collect predictions from each learner
            
        # TODO : weighted vote for each sample's prediction across all learners, each learner's weight is stored in self.learner_weights
        predictionsOfLearners = np.array(predictionsOfLearners)
        unique_classes = np.unique(np.hstack([learner.predict(X) for learner in self.learners]))
        class_to_index = {cls: idx for idx, cls in enumerate(unique_classes)}
        
        n_samples = X.shape[0]
        n_classes = len(unique_classes)
        weighted_votes = np.zeros((n_samples, n_classes))
        
        for i, weight in enumerate(self.learner_weights):
            for j in range(n_samples):
                class_label = predictionsOfLearners[i, j]
                class_index = class_to_index[class_label] # Map label to index
                weighted_votes[j, class_index] += weight
                
        # TODO : make final prediction by considering the label which has highest weighted vote

        final_predictions_indices = np.argmax(weighted_votes, axis=1)
        final_prediction = np.array(unique_classes[final_predictions_indices])
        
        return final_prediction

📊 Comparison with Library Implementation:¶

  1. Accuracy :

    The Scikit-learn implementation achieves significantly higher accuracy (92.69%) compared to the scratch implementation (70.75%).

  2. Class-wise Metrics:

    • The Scikit-learn implementation has better precision, recall, and F1-scores for both classes.

    • For example, in the first class:

      • Precision improved from 68.67% to 91.68%.

      • Recall improved from 72.74% to 93.36%.

  3. Averages:

    • The library implementation consistently outperforms the manual version across weighted, micro, and macro averages.

    • For instance, the weighted average precision improved from 70.87% to 92.70%.

  4. Conclusion:

    The Scikit-learn implementation performs significantly better than the manual implementation due to its optimized algorithms and efficient handling of edge cases. However, the scratch implementation provides valuable insights into the mechanics of Boosting, making it a useful learning tool.
